{
  "id": "hearth_at_stillweir",
  "encounterTitle": "Hearth at Stillweir",
  "description": "A woodcutter's cottage at the edge of an imperial cart-path. The door is open, smoke comes from the chimney, and the man at the threshold watches you without dropping his axe.",
  "mapId": "settled_forest",
  "npcIds": [
    "woodcutter"
  ],
  "objective": "Speak with the woodcutter — and decide what you owe him.",
  "completionFlag": "stillweir_resolved",
  "customIntroduction": "The path bends past a low stone cottage tucked against the forest, smoke curling from the chimney, log piles stacked neat against the south wall. A wiry man in a stained leather apron stands in the doorway with a hand-axe loose at his hip, watching you come. He does not raise the axe. He does not lower it either. \"Travellers,\" he says. \"State your business before you come closer.\"",
  "customContext": "SETTING CUE: Stillweir is one of the unaffiliated holdings the New Empire has not bothered to absorb — a half-day from the nearest Bureau outpost, a full day from any White Cape post, and the woodcutter prefers to keep it that way. The man at the door is the cottage's only resident (npc id \"woodcutter\"). He is wary, polite, and unwilling to invite strangers in until they have given him a reason to. He has fresh information worth trading: bandits on the trail to the west (the scene of the \"tithe_on_the_trail\" encounter, if the GM wants to seed it), a Concordat patrol that came through two days ago looking for someone he claims not to know, and a half-burned licence he found by the path that he has hidden under a board. The player can earn his trust through honesty, a small gift, or skill checks (Persuasion / Insight). HE WILL NOT FIGHT unless attacked first or unless the player threatens his cottage. ESCALATION: If the player attacks or seriously threatens the woodcutter, call set_disposition on him to enemy, then trigger_combat; he will fight defensively with the hand-axe until reduced below 4 HP and then attempt to flee toward the dense trees east of the cottage. ROLEPLAY: he speaks plainly, like a man who has been alone for a long time and remembers what people are for. He does not talk about the Empire unless the player raises it; when he does, his answers are short and not loyal. CHAPTER COMPLETION: set_world_flag stillweir_resolved=true when the player leaves the cottage on any terms (helped, refused, robbed, killed).",
